Infection dynamics in bats are likely influenced by the unique ecology of this diverse group of mammals. There are several ways in which bats differ from other similarly sized mammals, including potential for rapid and widespread dispersal, highly gregarious social structures, long lifespans and high survival, with low fecundity (
 Calisher et al., 2006). The majority of the studies on bat infections to date have focused on bats and zoonotic viral infections, but the ecological generalities may be similar among bacterial (
 Kosoy et al., 2010; 
 Bai et al., 2011) and fungal infections of bats (e.g. 
 Histoplasma capsulatum, 
 Geomyces destructans) (
 Taylor et al., 2005; 
 Blehert et al., 2009; 
 Frick et al., 2010; 
 Foley et al., 2011; 
 Puechmaille et al., 2011). Although widely recognized, few studies have involved explicit hypothesis testing regarding pathogen associations and the unique ecological characteristics of bats.
